        System.out.println(&quot;name of table is: &quot; + table);
        System.out.println(&quot;column values are: &quot;);
    
        for (Strinc c : column) {
            System.out.println(c);
        }
    }

You can use an *enhanced-for* (also called *for-each*) loop:

    for (String s : column) {
        System.out.println(s);
    }

Or a normal `for` loop:

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; column.length; i++) {
        System.out.println(column[i]);
    }

If you use a `while` you will have to keep count of indices:

    int i = 0;
    while (i &lt; column.length) {
        System.out.println(column[i]);
        i++;
    }

**Note:**

Remember that `column` is an array: `String[] column`.

`nextLine()` is not a method for an array. Not only that, you used it incorrectly. You should have done this (if these methods were to exist): `while (column.hasNextLine())`

Assuming you would like to use a while loop to print your String array:

    int i = 0;
    while(i &lt; column.length)
    {
        System.out.println(column[i]);
        i++; // increment the index
    }


Or you could use a [for-each](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/for.html) loop (or &quot;enhanced-for&quot; loop, whatever it&#39;s called):

    for (String c : column) {
        System.out.println(c);
    }

Or even a classic for loop:

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; column.length; i++) {
